A solid steel shaft, 20 mm in diameter and 1 m long, is placed concentrically inside a hollow duralumin shaft with inside and outside diameters of 30 mm and 33 mm, respectively, and a length of 500 mm. The ends of the hollow shaft are rigidly fixed to the solid shaft. Determine (a) the torsional stiffness of the composite shaft, (b) the maximum torque to which the composite shaft may be subjected if the allowable shear stresses for steel and duralumin are 90 MPa and 30 MPa, respectively, and (c) the total angle of twist if the shaft is subjected to the torque determined in (b). Use {eq}{G}_{DU}

{/eq} = 25 GPa and {eq}{G}_{ST}

{/eq} = 84 GPa.

answer:
(a) The torsional stiffness of the composite shaft is given by:

{eq}K_{eq} = \frac{1}{\frac{1}{K_s} + \frac{1}{K_d}}

{/eq}

where {eq}K_s

{/eq} and {eq}K_d

{/eq} are the torsional stiffnesses of the solid steel shaft and the hollow duralumin shaft, respectively.

The torsional stiffness of the solid steel shaft is:

{eq}K_s = \frac{G_sJ_s}{L_s}

{/eq}

where {eq}G_s

{/eq} is the shear modulus of steel, {eq}J_s

{/eq} is the polar moment of inertia of the solid steel shaft, and {eq}L_s

{/eq} is the length of the solid steel shaft.

The torsional stiffness of the hollow duralumin shaft is:

{eq}K_d = \frac{G_dJ_d}{L_d}

{/eq}

where {eq}G_d

{/eq} is the shear modulus of duralumin, {eq}J_d

{/eq} is the polar moment of inertia of the hollow duralumin shaft, and {eq}L_d

{/eq} is the length of the hollow duralumin shaft.

Substituting the given values into the above equations, we get:

{eq}K_s = \frac{84 \times 10^9 \times \frac{\pi}{32} \times 0.02^4}{1} = 1319.46\;{\rm{N/m}}

{/eq}

{eq}K_d = \frac{25 \times 10^9 \times \frac{\pi}{32} \times (0.033^4 - 0.030^4)}{0.5} = 922.64\;{\rm{N/m}}

{/eq}

Therefore, the torsional stiffness of the composite shaft is:

{eq}K_{eq} = \frac{1}{\frac{1}{1319.46} + \frac{1}{922.64}} = 830.63\;{\rm{N/m}}

{/eq}

(b) The maximum torque to which the composite shaft may be subjected is given by:

{eq}T_{max} = \frac{\tau_{s,allow}J_s}{r_s} + \frac{\tau_{d,allow}J_d}{r_d}

{/eq}

where {eq}\tau_{s,allow}

{/eq} and {eq}\tau_{d,allow}

{/eq} are the allowable shear stresses for steel and duralumin, respectively, {eq}r_s

{/eq} is the radius of the solid steel shaft, and {eq}r_d

{/eq} is the radius of the hollow duralumin shaft.

Substituting the given values into the above equation, we get:

{eq}T_{max} = \frac{90 \times 10^6 \times \frac{\pi}{32} \times 0.02^4}{0.01} + \frac{30 \times 10^6 \times \frac{\pi}{32} \times (0.033^4 - 0.030^4)}{0.0165} = 193.97\;{\rm{N - m}}

{/eq}

Therefore, the maximum torque to which the composite shaft may be subjected is 193.97 N-m.

(c) The total angle of twist of the composite shaft is given by:

{eq}\theta = \frac{T_{max}}{K_{eq}}

{/eq}

Substituting the given values into the above equation, we get:

{eq}\theta = \frac{193.97}{830.63} = 0.233\;{\rm{rad}}

{/eq}

Therefore, the total angle of twist of the composite shaft is 0.233 rad.

