To find the average speed of the rocket over the interval {eq}[3, 6]{/eq}, we need to calculate the average rate of change of its position function. This is done by finding the difference in position between the end points and dividing by the time interval.

First, we evaluate the position function at {eq}t = 3{/eq} and {eq}t = 6{/eq}:

{eq}\begin{align*}

p(3) &= 2(3)^2 + 5(3) + 5 = 38\\

p(6) &= 2(6)^2 + 5(6) + 5 = 107

\end{align*}

{/eq}

Now, we calculate the average rate of change (average speed):

{eq}\begin{align*}

\text{Average speed} &= \frac{p(6) - p(3)}{6 - 3}\\

&= \frac{107 - 38}{3}\\

&= \frac{69}{3}\\

&= 23

\end{align*}

{/eq}

Therefore, over the three-second period from {eq}t = 3{/eq} to {eq}t = 6{/eq}, the rocket's average speed was 23 miles per second.
